1 Introduction

In response to declining sales performance, Galeries Lafayette has initiated a comprehensive research project aimed at deepening the understanding of customer perceptions and their impact on brand loyalty and engagement. This study focuses on identifying the key perceptual dimensions that shape the image of Galeries Lafayette and evaluating how these perceptions influence customer satisfaction, affective commitment, and behavioral intentions such as repurchase and co-creation.

The dataset consists of 553 observations and 45 variables, covering perceptions related to Galeries Lafayette. Variables include 22 image perception items (Im1â€“Im22), 4 cognitive credibility items (C_CR1â€“C_CR4), 3 corporate reputation items (C_REP1â€“C_REP3), 4 communication attitude items (COM_A1â€“COM_A4), 6 satisfaction measures (SAT_1â€“SAT_P6), and 3 trust measures (TRU_1â€“TRU_3).

Variables are primarily measured on an integer rating scale, likely corresponding to Likert-type responses.

Approximately 276 rows (about 50%!) contain at least one missing value. Excluding all NA rows would mean loosing a 50 % of data leading to weaker statistical power and less stable factors, hence FA will be cunducted using pairwise correlations for EFA and ML estimation with missing for CFA.

2 Question 1: What are the dimensions by which Galeries Lafayette is perceived? Please explain your findings and rational for your final result.

To address Question 1, we will conduct an Exploratory Factor Analysis (EFA) on the 22 image-related survey items (Im1 to Im22) to uncover the underlying perceptual dimensions by which customers evaluate Galeries Lafayette. These items reflect customer views on various aspects of the brand, as identified through prior qualitative interviews. The EFA will help identify coherent factor groupings that represent distinct brand image dimensions, which will then be validated through a Confirmatory Factor Analysis (CFA).

2.1 Testing the Suitability of Data for Factor Analysis

Before performing principal axis factoring, it is important to check whether the data is appropriate for factor analysis. This involves testing if the variables are sufficiently correlated and if the sample is adequate for extracting reliable factors.

Calculate correlation matrix

# Select only variables needed for the analysis
Images <- Data %>%
  select(
    Im1:Im22
  )

# Calculate correlation matrix with pairwise handling to avoid dropping rows 
cor_matrix_Images <- cor(Images, use = "pairwise.complete.obs")

# Create the correlation plot
ggcorrplot(round(cor_matrix_Images, 2),
           method = "square", 
           type = "lower", 
           show.diag = FALSE,
           lab = TRUE, lab_col = "black", hc.order = T, lab_size = 2)

Most values are sufficient for FA, although Im11 has weaker correlations.

Check adequacy of correlation matrix

# Due to NA present in the dataset run Bartlett's test manually on correlation matrix
cortest.bartlett(cor_matrix_Images, n = nrow(Images))

The suitability of the dataset for factor analysis was confirmed using Correlation matrix, Bartlettâ€™s Test of Sphericity, the Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin (KMO), MSA measures:

  • most of the correlations in the Correlation matrix exceed 0.3.
  • Bartlettâ€™s Test of Sphericity was significant (Ï‡Â²(231) = 9091.594, p < .001), indicating that the correlation matrix is suitable for factor analysis
  • The overall Kaiser-Meyer-Olkin (KMO) measure was 0.88, indicating meritorious sampling adequacy. All individual items exceeded the acceptable threshold of 0.80, supporting the suitability of the data for factor analysis.

These results support proceeding with exploratory factor analysis.

The eigenvalue analysis revealed that 6 factors had eigenvalues greater than 1, together explaining approximately 76% of the total variance. The first factor alone explained 40.88%, while the subsequent factors each explained between 5â€“10% of the variance.

Even though 7th and 8th factors have eigenvalues 0.77 and 0.72, which is less than 1 treshold, they still explain 79% (for 7 factors) and 82% (for 8), which is worth exploring as well.

# Scree plot

On the Scree-plot the elbow seems to be at 6th or 7th factors level.

To find out the right number of factors 3 possible solution with 6,7 and 8 factors shall be further explored with CFA.

Factor Loadings:
* Im9 (French Fashion): Loads weakly on MR2 (0.440) and also on MR5 (0.321) and MR6 (0.325) - very complex. * Im11 (High-quality Cosmetics): Loads weakly on MR2 (0.550) * Im16 (Professional Appearance Towards Customers): Loads on MR1 (0.467) and MR4 (0.364). * Im17 (Are Trendy): Loads weakly/complexly on MR1 (0.379), MR4 (0.303), MR5 (0.360), and MR6 (0.479). * Im18 (Are Hip): Loads weakly/complexly on MR1 (0.303), MR4 (0.306), MR5 (0.305), and MR6 (0.472). * Im19 (Professional Organization): Loads on MR1 (0.449) and MR4 (0.405).

  • Im9 (French Fashion) is vague, can relate to many things, should be removed.

  • Im11 (High-quality Cosmetics) has weak loading. Thinking by logic High-quality Cosmetics stands alone and doesnâ€™t directly relate to other variables. But since it doesnâ€™t cross load for the moment - keep it.

  • It seems that Im17 (Are Trendy) and Im18 (Are Hip) cross load on other factor due to they donâ€™t really relate to any of other variables and nees their own dimension that describes Trends. whether they need their own dimention or not - arguable.

  • Im16 (Professional Appearance Towards Customers) and Im19 (Professional Organization) represent Assortment but also Professionalism. The variable are vague thatâ€™s why they cross load.

# 6 Factor Model with Im9 removed shows better metrics:
model_6 <- "France =~ Im6 + Im7 + Im8  + Im10 + Im14
          Assortment =~ Im1 + Im2 + Im15 + Im16 + Im19
          Aesthetic =~ Im3 + Im4 + Im5

Interpretation of the Reliability and Validity Analysis for 6-Factor Model (with Correlated Errors):

This section details the reliability and validity assessment for the 6-factor Confirmatory Factor Analysis (CFA) model, which included residual covariances between Im6-Im7 and Im1-Im2 residual covariance.

Individual Item Reliability (IIR)

IIR represents the proportion of variance in each observed indicator explained by its corresponding latent factor (effectively the squared standardized loading).

  • High Values (Good): Items showing strong reliability (typically > 0.70), indicating they are well-explained by their respective factors, include: Im4 (0.94), Im17 (0.95), Im3 (0.88), Im8 (0.80), Im12 (0.76), Im13 (0.73), Im22 (0.76), Im20 (0.72), Im18 (0.73).
  • Moderate Values: Items with moderate reliability include: Im15 (0.67), Im16 (0.54), Im19 (0.58), Im5 (0.58), Im21 (0.62).
  • Low Values (Problematic): Several items exhibit low reliability, suggesting they are not strongly representative of their assigned factors in this model configuration:
    • Items for the France factor: Im6 (0.24), Im7 (0.35), Im10 (0.32), Im14 (0.33).
    • Items for the Assortment factor: Im1 (0.28), Im2 (0.25).
    • Item Im11 (0.37) for the Quality factor. Much of the variance in these low-reliability items remains unexplained by their factors within this model.

Composite Reliability (CR)

CR assesses the internal consistency of the indicators for each latent construct. A value > 0.70 is generally considered acceptable.

  • Acceptable/Marginal:
    • France (0.75): Meets the minimum threshold, but this value should be viewed cautiously given the very low IIR of its individual indicators.
    • Assortment (0.78): Appears acceptable, however, this also masks the poor reliability of items Im1 and Im2 within the factor.
  • Good/Excellent:
    • Aesthetic (0.92), Quality (0.83), Atmosphere (0.87), Trends (0.91): These factors demonstrate good to excellent internal consistency, suggesting their indicators work well together.

Average Variance Extracted (AVE)

AVE measures the average amount of variance explained by the latent factor across its indicators, indicating convergent validity. An AVE > 0.50 is generally required.

  • FAIL:
    • France (0.37): Fails to meet the threshold.
    • Assortment (0.42): Fails to meet the threshold. For both factors, the average indicator variance explained by the construct is less than the variance due to error/uniqueness, indicating poor convergent validity.
  • PASS:
    • Aesthetic (0.80), Quality (0.62), Atmosphere (0.70), Trends (0.84): These factors meet or exceed the 0.50 criterion, demonstrating acceptable to excellent convergent validity.

Discriminant Validity (via Fornell-Larcker Criterion)

Discriminant validity assesses whether latent factors represent truly distinct concepts. Using the Fornell-Larcker criterion, the AVE of a factor should be greater than its squared correlation (shared variance) with any other factor.

  • France (AVE=0.37): Appears distinct from other factors based on this criterion (all squared correlations with France are below 0.37).
  • Assortment (AVE=0.42):
    • vs.Â Aesthetic: Squared correlation = 0.43. Since 0.43 > 0.42, this comparison FAILS.
    • vs.Â Quality: Squared correlation = 0.40. Since 0.40 < 0.42, this comparison PASSES.
    • vs.Â Trends: Squared correlation = 0.46. Since 0.46 > 0.42, this comparison FAILS. The Assortment factor lacks discriminant validity against the Aesthetic and Trends factors within this model.
  • Other Factors: Aesthetic (AVE=0.80), Quality (AVE=0.62), Atmosphere (AVE=0.70), and Trends (AVE=0.84) all demonstrate adequate discriminant validity amongst themselves and against France, as their AVE values are greater than their respective squared correlations with other factors.

Conclusion on Modified 6-Factor Model Reliability & Validity

While modifying the 6-factor model by adding specific residual covariances (Im6~~Im7, Im1~~Im2) may improve overall fit indices compared to the basic 6-factor model, this detailed assessment reveals persistent and fundamental weaknesses. The France and Assortment factors suffer from poor item reliability (low IIR) for multiple indicators and fail to achieve adequate convergent validity (AVE < 0.50). Furthermore, the Assortment factor demonstrates poor discriminant validity against Aesthetic and Trends. These results strongly indicate that the 6-factor structure, even when adjusted, does not provide a reliable or valid representation of the underlying constructs, particularly for France and Assortment. This analysis reinforces the decision to explore alternative structures, such as the 7-factor model.

  1. Poor Overall Fit: The primary issue is that this model does not fit the data well (RMSEA=0.084, CFI/TLI borderline). This poor fit renders detailed interpretation of reliability and validity less meaningful, as the parameter estimates themselves are suspect.

Conclusion: This model is not the best solution. The analysis highlights the persistent problems stemming from forcing items (like Im16, Im19) onto factors where they donâ€™t belong. 8-factor structure could provide a more accurate and statistically sound representation of the data.

Interpretation of the Reliability and Validity Analysis for 7-Factor Model (with Correlated Errors)

This section details the reliability and validity assessment for the 7-factor Confirmatory Factor Analysis (CFA) model (fit_7_cov). This model excludes indicators Im8 and Im9 (originally associated with France) and includes residual covariances between Im1-Im2 and Im16-Im19.

Individual Item Reliability (IIR):

  • High Values (Good): Items showing strong reliability (typically > 0.70), indicating they are well-explained by their respective factors, include: Im7 (0.91), Im15 (0.71), Im3 (0.88), Im4 (0.94), Im12 (0.76), Im13 (0.73), Im20 (0.72), Im22 (0.77), Im17 (0.95), Im18 (0.73), Im10 (0.85), Im14 (0.91).
  • Moderate Values: Im6 (0.66), Im5 (0.58), Im21 (0.61) show moderate/adequate reliability.
  • Low Values (Problematic): A significant number of items exhibit low reliability, suggesting they are not strongly representative of their assigned factors in this model configuration:
    • Items within the Assortment factor: Im1 (0.31), Im2 (0.27), Im16 (0.34), Im19 (0.38). These items have very substantial variance unexplained by the Assortment factor.
    • Item Im11 (0.38) for the Quality factor also shows low reliability.

Composite Reliability (CR)

  • Acceptable/Marginal:
    • Assortment (0.75): This value barely meets the minimum threshold. However, given the extremely low IIR for four out of its five indicators (Im1, Im2, Im16, Im19), this CR value is highly misleading and does not reflect genuine high internal consistency for this set of items as indicators of this specific factor.
  • Good/Excellent:
    • France (0.88), Aesthetic (0.92), Quality (0.83), Atmosphere (0.87), Trends (0.91), Food (0.94): These factors demonstrate good to excellent internal consistency.

Average Variance Extracted (AVE)

  • FAIL:
    • Assortment (0.37): Fails substantially to meet the 0.50 threshold. This indicates poor convergent validity. On average, the Assortment factor explains only 37% of the variance in its indicators; more variance is attributable to error/uniqueness.
  • PASS:
    • France (0.79), Aesthetic (0.80), Quality (0.62), Atmosphere (0.70), Trends (0.84), Food (0.88): These factors meet or exceed the 0.50 criterion, demonstrating acceptable to excellent convergent validity.

Discriminant Validity (via Fornell-Larcker Criterion)

Discriminant validity assesses whether latent factors represent truly distinct concepts. Using the Fornell-Larcker criterion, the AVE of a factor should be greater than its squared correlation (shared variance) with any other factor.

  • Assortment (AVE=0.37):
    • vs.Â Aesthetic: Squared correlation = 0.41. Since 0.41 > 0.37, this comparison FAILS.
    • vs.Â Quality: Squared correlation = 0.42. Since 0.42 > 0.37, this comparison FAILS.
    • vs.Â Trends: Squared correlation = 0.46. Since 0.46 > 0.37, this comparison FAILS. The Assortment factor lacks discriminant validity against the Aesthetic, Quality, and Trends factors within this model. It shares more variance with these other factors than is captured, on average, by its own indicators.
  • Other Factors: France (AVE=0.79), Aesthetic (AVE=0.80), Quality (AVE=0.62), Atmosphere (AVE=0.70), Trends (AVE=0.84), and Food (AVE=0.88) all demonstrate adequate discriminant validity based on this criterion, as their AVEs are greater than their squared correlations with all other factors.

Conclusion on Modified 7-Factor Model (fit_7_cov) Reliability & Validity

Despite achieving excellent overall model fit statistics (RMSEA=0.048, CFI=0.976, etc.) through the removal of Im8/Im9 and the addition of residual covariances (Im1~~Im2, Im16~~Im19), this detailed assessment reveals critical flaws in measurement quality, particularly for the Assortment factor:

  1. Poor Item Reliability: Four out of five indicators for Assortment (Im1, Im2, Im16, Im19) show very low reliability (IIR < 0.40). Item Im11 also shows low reliability for Quality.
  2. Lack of Convergent Validity: The Assortment factor fails significantly on convergent validity (AVE = 0.37).
  3. Lack of Discriminant Validity: The Assortment factor is not sufficiently distinct from Aesthetic, Quality, and Trends.
  4. Reliance on Modifications: The modelâ€™s good fit relies on residual covariances, especially Im16~~Im19, which likely compensates for omitting a distinct â€œProfessionalismâ€ factor identified in 8-factor analyses.

Therefore, while the global fit indices are appealing, this specific model (fit_7_cov) suffers from severe measurement issues for the Assortment construct. It is not recommended as the final model due to the invalid and unreliable measurement of this factor. The 8-factor structure appears necessary to adequately represent the distinct dimensions within the data, particularly regarding the items related to professionalism (Im16, Im19).

Reliability and Validity Analysis for Refined 8-Factor Model (fit_8)

This section details the reliability and validity assessment for the refined 8-factor Confirmatory Factor Analysis (CFA) model (fit_8). This model includes the â€œProfessionalismâ€ factor (Im16, Im19) and excludes indicators Im8, Im9, and Im15 based on previous refinement steps. Indicator Im11 remains within the Quality factor.

Individual Item Reliability (IIR)

IIR represents the proportion of variance in each observed indicator explained by its corresponding latent factor (effectively the squared standardized loading).

  • High Values (Good): The majority of items show strong reliability (typically > 0.70), indicating they are well-explained by their respective factors: Im7 (0.91), Im1 (0.96), Im2 (0.81), Im3 (0.88), Im4 (0.94), Im12 (0.76), Im13 (0.73), Im20 (0.71), Im22 (0.77), Im17 (0.94), Im18 (0.73), Im10 (0.85), Im14 (0.91), Im19 (0.73).
  • Moderate Values: Im6 (0.66), Im5 (0.58), Im21 (0.61), Im16 (0.59) show moderate to adequate reliability.
  • Low Values (Potentially Problematic):
    • Item Im11 (0.38) for the Quality factor remains the indicator with the lowest reliability, confirming it is the weakest link in the measurement model.

Composite Reliability (CR)

CR assesses the internal consistency of the indicators for each latent construct. A value > 0.70 is generally considered acceptable.

  • Excellent: France (0.88), Assortment (0.94), Aesthetic (0.92), Quality (0.83), Atmosphere (0.87), Trends (0.91), Food (0.94) all demonstrate excellent internal consistency. Their respective indicators work well together.
  • Acceptable: Professionalism (0.79) shows acceptable internal consistency, meeting the threshold.

Average Variance Extracted (AVE)

AVE measures the average amount of variance explained by the latent factor across its indicators, indicating convergent validity. An AVE > 0.50 is generally required.

  • PASS (Excellent): France (0.79), Assortment (0.88), Aesthetic (0.80), Quality (0.62), Atmosphere (0.70), Trends (0.84), Food (0.88), Professionalism (0.66). All factors strongly exceed the 0.50 threshold, demonstrating good to excellent convergent validity. The latent factors explain, on average, a substantial majority of the variance in their indicators.

Discriminant Validity (via Fornell-Larcker Criterion)

Discriminant validity assesses whether latent factors represent truly distinct concepts. Using the Fornell-Larcker criterion, the AVE of a factor should be greater than its squared correlation (shared variance) with any other factor.

  • France (AVE=0.79): Distinct (max RÂ² vs Food â‰ˆ 0.34).
  • Assortment (AVE=0.88): Distinct (max RÂ² vs Professionalism â‰ˆ 0.36).
  • Aesthetic (AVE=0.80): Distinct (max RÂ² vs Professionalism â‰ˆ 0.43).
  • Quality (AVE=0.62): Distinct (max RÂ² vs Trends â‰ˆ 0.32).
  • Atmosphere (AVE=0.70): Distinct (max RÂ² vs Trends â‰ˆ 0.27).
  • Trends (AVE=0.84): Distinct (max RÂ² vs Professionalism â‰ˆ 0.36).
  • Food (AVE=0.88): Distinct (max RÂ² vs France â‰ˆ 0.34).
  • Professionalism (AVE=0.66): Distinct (max RÂ² vs Aesthetic â‰ˆ 0.43).

All factors demonstrate adequate discriminant validity based on the Fornell-Larcker criterion in this model. The AVE for each factor is comfortably higher than its squared correlation with any other factor.

Conclusion on Refined 8-Factor Model (fit_8) Reliability & Validity

This refined 8-factor model (fit_8) demonstrates strong psychometric properties:

  1. Excellent Overall Fit: The model fits the data extremely well, providing a solid foundation for assessing reliability and validity.
  2. Strong Convergent Validity: All factors meet and exceed the AVE > 0.50 criterion.
  3. Strong Discriminant Validity: All factors are shown to be distinct from one another based on the Fornell-Larcker criterion.
  4. Good Internal Consistency: All factors exhibit good to excellent composite reliability (CR > 0.70).
  5. Generally Good Item Reliability: Most individual items reliably measure their intended factors. The primary exception is Im11 within the Quality factor, which consistently shows lower reliability compared to other items.

Conclusion: This model (fit_8) is a very strong candidate for the final model. The only remaining consideration is the relatively weak performance of Im11. Although the standardized loading for Im11 (â‰ˆ 0.615) is lower relative to other indicators in the final model, it remains statistically significant (p < 0.001). This loading indicates that Im11 still shares approximately 38% of its variance with the â€˜Qualityâ€™ factor, representing a substantive, non-negligible contribution to the constructâ€™s measurement within this well-fitting model.

2.2.4 Overall Conclusion: Model Comparison and Selection

The objective of this analysis was to identify the most appropriate factor structure underlying the 22 Im items measuring perceptions of GLB. Several models based on Exploratory Factor Analysis (EFA) suggesting 6, 7, and 8 factors were specified and tested using Confirmatory Factor Analysis (CFA). This was followed by iterative refinement based on fit statistics, parameter estimates, and theoretical considerations to arrive at a final, well-fitting, and theoretically sound model.

Evaluation of 6-Factor Models

The initial 6-factor EFA revealed a problematic structure. Notably, it merged conceptually distinct items (e.g., related to France and Food) into single factors and exhibited numerous complex cross-loadings. The corresponding CFA confirmed this inadequacy with extremely poor model fit.

Attempts were made to improve fit by adding residual covariances based on modification indices (resulting in model fit_6_cor). While this approach resulted in statistically acceptable global fit indices, a detailed examination revealed critical weaknesses in local fit and measurement quality:

  • The crucial â€œFranceâ€ and â€œAssortmentâ€ factors demonstrated unacceptably low Average Variance Extracted (AVE < 0.50), indicating poor convergent validity.
  • The â€œAssortmentâ€ factor also showed poor discriminant validity against several other factors.
  • The reliance on potentially atheoretical residual covariances further weakened this solution.

Consequently, the 6-factor structure, even with modifications, was deemed fundamentally flawed and rejected.

Evaluation of 7-Factor Models

The initial 7-factor CFA structure, mapped directly from the EFA, also exhibited poor overall model fit (RMSEA â‰ˆ 0.084, CFI/TLI â‰ˆ 0.90), indicating inadequacy. Key issues included:

  • The cross-loading behaviour of Im8.
  • The problematic assignment of Im16 and Im19 to the â€œAssortmentâ€ factor, where they loaded weakly.

Adding residual covariances (Model fit_7_cov) substantially improved global fit indices to excellent levels (RMSEA â‰ˆ 0.048, CFI â‰ˆ 0.976). However, this model still suffered from poor measurement quality for the â€œAssortmentâ€ factor (AVE = 0.37) and relied on model modifications that likely masked the need for a distinct â€œProfessionalismâ€ factor.

Therefore, while better than the 6-factor solutions, the 7-factor structure, even when modified, did not provide an optimal representation of the data and was not selected as the final model.

Evaluation of 8-Factor Models

The 8-factor EFA provided a cleaner structure, notably suggesting Im16 and Im19 formed a distinct factor, subsequently labelled â€œProfessionalismâ€. The initial 8-factor CFA confirmed this structure was promising, showing better fit than the initial 7-factor model.

Subsequent refinement involved removing items identified as problematic across analyses:

  • Im8 and Im9 (weak/complex loadings on â€œFranceâ€, cross-loading issues).
  • Im15 (weakest loading on â€œAssortmentâ€ after other removals).

This iterative process led to the final recommended model (fit_8): an 8-factor structure with â€œProfessionalismâ€ as a distinct factor, and items Im8, Im9, and Im15 removed. This model demonstrated outstanding statistical fit across all indices (RMSEA = 0.044, CFI = 0.982, TLI = 0.975, SRMR = 0.029), strongly indicating it aligns well with the observed data.

Measurement Quality of Recommended 8-Factor Model (fit_8)

This model exhibited strong psychometric properties:

  • Reliability: Excellent Composite Reliability (CR > 0.79) for all factors.
  • Convergent Validity: Excellent Average Variance Extracted (AVE > 0.62) for all factors, indicating indicators strongly converge on their respective constructs.
  • Discriminant Validity: All factors demonstrated clear discriminant validity based on the Fornell-Larcker criterion (AVE > RÂ² with other factors).
  • Item Reliability: Most indicators showed strong individual reliability (high squared loadings). The only exception was Im11 (â€œHigh-quality Cosmeticsâ€) loading on â€œQualityâ€ (Std. loading â‰ˆ 0.615), which showed moderate reliability.

Final Model Justification (fit_8)

The refined 8-factor model (fit_8) is selected as the best solution. It provides a superior statistical fit compared to the 6- and 7-factor alternatives and addresses the structural misspecifications inherent in those models by identifying a distinct and meaningful â€œProfessionalismâ€ factor. This model demonstrates strong reliability, convergent validity, and discriminant validity for all constructs.

The decision was made to retain Im11 within this final model despite its lower relative loading, based on:

  1. The excellent overall model fit achieved with the item included.
  2. Its contribution to the content validity of the â€œQualityâ€ factor (representing product quality alongside brand prestige).
  3. The benefit of maintaining three indicators for factor stability.

In conclusion, the final 8-factor model (fit_8), incorporating the â€œProfessionalismâ€ dimension and refined through the removal of items Im8, Im9, and Im15, offers the most statistically robust, reliable, valid, and theoretically coherent representation of the structure underlying the perception of GLB based on the analyzed data.

3.1 Comparison of Drivers for Satisfaction and Affective Commitment

The analysis investigates whether the same store image perceptions drive Satisfaction and Affective Commitment. The results indicate that while there is some overlap, the primary drivers for each construct differ significantly.

3.1.1 Key Findings:

Partial Overlap: Both Satisfaction and Affective Commitment are significantly and positively influenced by perceptions related to France (Î² = 0.115 for SAT, Î² = 0.192 for AC) and Assortment (Î² = 0.197 for SAT, Î² = 0.114 for AC).

Distinct Primary Drivers: * The strongest positive predictor for Satisfaction is Professionalism (Î² = 0.479, p < 0.001). However, Professionalism does not have a significant direct effect on Affective Commitment (p = 0.129). * The strongest positive predictor for Affective Commitment is Atmosphere (Î² = 0.411, p < 0.001). Conversely, Atmosphere does not have a significant direct effect on Satisfaction (p = 0.170).

Differing Negative/Null Effects: * Aesthetic perception has a significant negative impact on Satisfaction (Î² = -0.152, p = 0.011) but no significant effect on Affective Commitment (p = 0.659). * Quality perception has a marginally significant negative impact on Affective Commitment (Î² = -0.115, p = 0.058) but no significant effect on Satisfaction (p = 0.613).

3.1.2 Conclusion:

The mechanisms driving Satisfaction and Affective Commitment are not the same, although they share some common antecedents (France, Assortment). Satisfaction appears more strongly linked to the perceived Professionalism and negatively related to Aesthetics, while Affective Commitment is more strongly driven by the storeâ€™s Atmosphere and potentially negatively related to Quality. This suggests these are distinct psychological responses influenced differently by various facets of the store image.

3.2 Mediation Role of Satisfaction and Affective Commitment

The analysis strongly supports the role of Satisfaction and Affective Commitment as mediators between store image perceptions and behavioral intentions.

3.2.1 Evidence for Mediation:

Non-Significant Direct Effects: The direct paths specified from the eight store image dimensions to the final outcomes (Repurchase Intention paths c1-c8; Cocreation Intention paths c9-c16) were overwhelmingly non-significant. This indicates that store image perceptions do not directly translate into these specific behavioral intentions in this model.

Significant Indirect Effects: As detailed in the parameterEstimates output under defined parameters (:=), numerous significant indirect effects were found. For example: * Professionalism -> Satisfaction -> Repurchase Intention (Î² = 0.152, p < 0.001) * Atmosphere -> Affective Commitment -> Repurchase Intention (Î² = 0.145, p < 0.001) * Atmosphere -> Affective Commitment -> Cocreation Intention (Î² = 0.155, p < 0.001) * Significant Mediator-Outcome Paths: The paths from the mediators to the outcomes were significant: * Satisfaction -> Repurchase Intention (Î² = 0.318, p < 0.001) * Affective Commitment -> Repurchase Intention (Î² = 0.354, p < 0.001) * Affective Commitment -> Cocreation Intention (Î² = 0.377, p < 0.001) * Satisfaction -> Cocreation Intention (Î² = -0.190, p = 0.007)

Outcomes Mediated: Based on this evidence, Satisfaction and Affective Commitment mediate the impact of store image perceptions on both modeled outcomes:

Repurchase Intention: The influence of store image dimensions like Professionalism, Assortment, France, and Atmosphere on the intention to repurchase is channeled through Satisfaction and/or Affective Commitment.

Cocreation Intention: The influence of store image dimensions (particularly Atmosphere and France via Affective Commitment, and Professionalism/Assortment via Satisfaction, albeit negatively in the latter case) on the intention to co-create is channeled through Affective Commitment and Satisfaction.

3.2.2 Conclusion:

The model strongly supports the hypothesis that Satisfaction and Affective Commitment act as crucial intermediate mechanisms, translating perceptions of the storeâ€™s image into subsequent behavioral intentions like Repurchase Intention and Cocreation Intention. The direct impact of image perceptions on these intentions appears minimal once the mediating variables are accounted for.
